      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented QA procedures and version control; user verification of installation and solver settings.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 employed under a validated installation with documented version control and change management. Solver release notes and known issue log reviewed; no open issues relevant to rotating machinery hemolysis simulations identified. QA documentation satisfies MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmark cases from standard test suite demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations for incompressible rotating flow.",
      "rationale": "Fluent benchmark cases for lid-driven cavity and Taylor-Couette flow reproduced within 0.5% of published reference solutions. Rotating reference frame implementation verified against analytical solutions for solid-body rotation. Code verification requirements at MRL 2 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) reported for all primary quantities of interest; apparent order of convergence verified; discretization uncertainty formally quantified and shown to be below 5% of the QoI range.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed (coarse 4.2 M cells, medium 9.8 M cells, fine 21.3 M cells). GCI values for volume-averaged shear stress were below 6.1% on the medium-to-fine transition, indicating acceptable convergence for engineering purposes. The simulation team notes that near-wall resolution in the impeller tip-clearance region remains a known challenge for this geometry class, and the achieved GCI marginally exceeds the 5% threshold at two operating points. Given that the hemolysis index differences between medium and fine meshes are within measurement uncertainty of the experimental reference data, the team considers the discretization error acceptable in context. The overall CFD workflow is mature and the model has been applied to analogous pump geometries with consistent results."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, rotational speed, flow rate, temperature) documented and matched to simulation boundary conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental conditions fully documented: bovine blood analog (glycerol-water, viscosity 3.5 cP ± 0.1 cP), five operating points spanning 2–6 L/min at 2500–3500 RPM. Simulation boundary conditions set to match measured values; temperature maintained at 37 °C ± 0.5 °C in both experiment and model. Test condition correspondence confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics (e.g., normalized index of agreement, RMSE) computed for hemolysis index and pressure rise; model predictions within two experimental standard deviations at all operating points.",
      "rationale": "Normalized hemolysis index predictions fall within ±18% of experimental mean values across all five operating points; RMSE of 0.08 relative hemolysis index units. Pressure-flow curve predictions within 4% of measured values. Quantitative comparison satisfies MRL 2 output comparison requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (relative hemolysis index, volume-averaged shear stress, scalar stress exposure) directly map to the clinical decision criterion (RH < 1) and are computable from the simulation outputs.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and derived relative hemolysis index (RH). Both quantities are directly computed from CFD stress field outputs using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model. The mapping from simulation output to clinical acceptance criterion (RH < 1) is explicit and well-established in the literature. QoI relevance is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
